<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="38" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="29.[498,1089,1383,1480]" pageId="29" pageNumber="38">
A KEY FOR THE SPECIES 
<collectionCode box="[873,937,1383,1409]" pageId="29" pageNumber="38">AND</collectionCode>
GROUPS OF THE AFROTROPICAL 
<taxonomicName authorityName="DUDA" authorityYear="1920" box="[836,1089,1419,1445]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Poecilosomella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[836,1089,1419,1445]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="38">POECILOSOMELLA</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(incl. species of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="THOMSON" baseAuthorityYear="1869" box="[732,869,1454,1480]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Poecilosomella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angulata">
<emphasis box="[732,869,1454,1480]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="38">P. angulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="31" lastPageNumber="40" pageId="29" pageNumber="38" type="key">
<key lastPageId="31" lastPageNumber="40" pageId="29" pageNumber="38">
<keyStep pageId="29" pageNumber="38">
<paragraph blockId="29.[317,1270,1524,1585]" pageId="29" pageNumber="38">
<keyLead pageId="29" pageNumber="38">1 Fore tarsomeres 2–5 or all the fore tarsi white. 2 well developed pairs of katepisternal setae. 2</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[317,1270,1612,1673]" pageId="29" pageNumber="38">
<keyLead pageId="29" pageNumber="38">– Fore tarsomeres incl. basitarsus may be light (yellow) but not white, or, fore tarsomeres 1 to 3 white. Anterior katepisternal seta may be reduced. 3</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep lastPageId="30" lastPageNumber="39" pageId="29" pageNumber="38">
<paragraph blockId="29.[317,1270,1700,1797]" pageId="29" pageNumber="38">
<keyLead pageId="29" pageNumber="38">
2 Wing clear, only apex of vein 
<collectionCode box="[754,774,1700,1726]" country="Chile" name="Departamento de Geologia, Universidad de Chile" pageId="29" pageNumber="38">R</collectionCode>
<subScript attach="left" box="[773,803,1714,1730]" fontSize="7" pageId="29" pageNumber="38">2+3</subScript>
diffuse brown. Vein 
<collectionCode box="[1046,1066,1700,1726]" country="Chile" name="Departamento de Geologia, Universidad de Chile" pageId="29" pageNumber="38">R</collectionCode>
<subScript attach="left" box="[1065,1095,1714,1730]" fontSize="7" pageId="29" pageNumber="38">2+3</subScript>
without even a short vein appendage. Postgonite (
<figureCitation box="[829,918,1735,1761]" captionStart="Figs 52–57" captionStartId="23.[317,360,1683,1704]" captionTargetBox="[329,1255,426,1650]" captionTargetId="figure-10@23.[329,1258,424,1654]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="Figs 52–57. Poecilosomella hyalipennis HACKMAN, male postabdomen and genitalia.52 = outlineof sternite 5 in ventral view and medio-caudal part of the sternite in higher magnification, 53 = epandrium with cerci, surstyli and subepandrial sclerite, caudal view, 54 = surstylus in its broadest extension (a sublateral view), 55 = postgonite, in broadest view, 56 = same, caudal view, 57 = apical thread-like process of phallus with contours of distiphallus. Scales: 0.2 mm for Figs 52–53, 0.1 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5731968" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5731968/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="38">Fig. 55</figureCitation>
) with narrow basal part and broad apical part. 
<taxonomicName authority="HACKMAN, 1965" authorityName="HACKMAN" authorityYear="1965" box="[891,1270,1771,1797]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Poecilosomella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hyalipennis">
<emphasis box="[891,1059,1771,1797]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="38">P. hyalipennis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="HACKMAN, W." box="[1066,1270,1771,1797]" pageId="29" pageNumber="38" pagination="485 - 503" refId="ref16631" refString="HACKMAN, W. (1965) Diptera (Brachycera): Sphaeroceridae (Borboridae). South African Animal Life, Lund 11: 485 - 503." type="journal article" year="1965">HACKMAN, 1965</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[317,1270,439,571]" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">
<keyLead pageId="30" pageNumber="39">
– Wing richly patterned (
<figureCitation box="[688,778,439,465]" captionStart="Figs 69–72" captionStartId="28.[317,360,1747,1768]" captionTargetBox="[317,1269,1155,1703]" captionTargetId="graphics-394@28.[317,1269,1155,1703]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="Figs 69–72. Wings of Poecilosomella spp. n. 69 = P. additionalis sp. n. (paratype female); 70 = P. duploseriata sp. n. (paratype male), 71 = P. setimanus sp. n. (holotype male); 72 = P. setosissima sp. n." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5731976" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5731976/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">Fig. 69</figureCitation>
), 
<collectionCode box="[801,821,439,465]" country="Chile" name="Departamento de Geologia, Universidad de Chile" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">R</collectionCode>
<subScript attach="left" box="[820,850,453,469]" fontSize="7" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">2+3</subScript>
with or without a vein appendage. Postgonite long, broadened at its middle (
<figureCitation box="[896,972,475,501]" captionStart="Figs 5–8" captionStartId="4.[317,360,1744,1765]" captionTargetBox="[321,1267,981,1704]" captionTargetId="figure-170@4.[317,1269,978,1706]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 5–8. Poecilosomella additionalis sp. n., paratype male, genitalia.5 = surstylus in broadest extension, 6 = same, caudal process in higher magnification, 7 = postgonite, in broadest (sublateral) view, 8 = basiphallus, lateral view. Scales: 0.2 mm for Fig. 5, 0.1 mm for Figs 6–8" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5731948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5731948/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">Figs 7</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[985,1017,475,501]" captionStart="Figs 9–14" captionStartId="6.[317,360,1686,1707]" captionTargetBox="[361,1227,420,1657]" captionTargetId="figure-16@6.[359,1228,418,1658]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 9–14. Poecilosomella pallidimana (DUDA), male postabdomen and genitalia. 9 = sternite 5, ventral view (outset: medial lobe in higher magnification), 10 = epandrium with modified cerci, subepandrial sclerite, anal plates and surstyli, subcaudal view, perpendicular to cerci (most of the epandrial setae omitted), 11 = surstylus in broadest extension, 12 = same, caudal process in higher magnification, 13 = postgonite, in broadest (sublateral) view, 14 = basiphallus, lateral view. Scales: 0.2 mm for Figs 9–11, 0.1 mm for Figs 12–14" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5731950" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5731950/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">13</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName box="[660,835,510,536]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Poecilosomella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pallidimana">
<emphasis box="[660,835,510,536]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">P. pallidimana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group (
<taxonomicName authority="Papp, 2010" authorityName="Papp" authorityYear="2010" box="[1019,1192,510,536]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Poecilosomella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="additionalis" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[1019,1192,510,536]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">P. additionalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1199,1264,510,536]" pageId="30" pageNumber="39" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(DUDA, 1925))" baseAuthorityName="DUDA" baseAuthorityYear="1925" box="[911,1269,545,571]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Poecilosomella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pallidimana">
<emphasis box="[911,1086,545,571]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">P. pallidimana</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="DUDA, O." box="[1101,1250,545,571]" pageId="30" pageNumber="39" pagination="5 - 215" refId="ref16563" refString="DUDA, O. (1925) Die aussereuropaischen Arten der Gattung Leptocera Olivier - Limosina Macquart (Dipteren) mit Berucksichtigung der europaischen Arten. Archiv fur Naturgeschichte 90 A (1924): 5 - 215." type="journal article" year="1925">DUDA, 1925</bibRefCitation>
))
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="30" pageNumber="39">
<paragraph blockId="30.[317,1270,598,730]" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">
<keyLead pageId="30" pageNumber="39">
3 Cercal part of the male epandrial complex with a simple sagittal projection (
<figureCitation box="[416,503,633,659]" captionStart="Figs 33–35" captionStartId="16.[317,360,1757,1778]" captionTargetBox="[322,1265,735,1722]" captionTargetId="figure-156@16.[317,1269,729,1725]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Figs 33–35. Poecilosomella parangulata sp. n., paratype male. 33 = hind tibia, dorsal view, 34 = sternite 5, ventral view, 35 = epandrium with modified cerci and subepandrial sclerite, caudal view. Scales: 0.2 mm for Figs 34–35, 0.4 mm for Fig. 33" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5731960" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5731960/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">Fig. 35</figureCitation>
), surstylus compact (i.e. lobes not long or emerging, 
<figureCitation box="[1122,1257,633,659]" captionStart="Figs 36–41" captionStartId="18.[317,360,1694,1715]" captionTargetBox="[348,1241,433,1666]" captionTargetId="figure-16@18.[343,1244,424,1666]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Figs 36–41. Poecilosomella parangulata sp. n., paratype male, postabdomen and genitalia. 36–37 = surstylus in broadest (sublateral) view: 36 = outer view, 37 = inner (medial) view, 38 = hypandrium, dorsal view, 39 = postgonite in widest extension, i.e. sublateral view, 40 = basiphallus and phallapodeme, lateral view (outset: caudal part in higher magnification), 41 = distiphallus, dorsal view. Scales: 0.2 mm for Figs 36–38, 40, 0.1 mm for Figs 39, 41" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5731962" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5731962/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">Figs 36–37</figureCitation>
). Mid basitarsus (usually shorter) with thick black setae, at least a complete anteroventral row, always present. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="THOMSON" baseAuthorityYear="1869" box="[818,955,704,730]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Poecilosomella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angulata">
<emphasis box="[818,955,704,730]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">P. angulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group 5
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[317,1270,756,853]" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">
<keyLead pageId="30" pageNumber="39">
– Cerci and surstylus are different (e.g. 
<figureCitation box="[853,987,756,782]" captionStart="Figs 46–51" captionStartId="21.[317,360,1707,1728]" captionTargetBox="[328,1261,567,1674]" captionTargetId="figure-77@21.[321,1264,563,1678]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Figs 46–51. Poecilosomella duploseriata sp. n., paratype male, genitalia. 46 = ventral part of epandrium with cerci and subepandrial sclerite, caudal view, 47 = surstylus in broadest extension (a sublateral view), 48 = outline of surstylus, caudal view at its longest extension, 49 = hypandrium, ventral view, 50 = postgonite in broadest (sublateral) view, 51 = phallus, phallapodeme and post- gonite, lateral view. Scales: 0.2 mm for Figs 46–49, 51, 0.1 mm for Fig. 50" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5731966" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5731966/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">Figs 46–47</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[999,1077,756,782]" captionStart="Figs 58–63" captionStartId="25.[317,360,1677,1698]" captionTargetBox="[329,1262,417,1645]" captionTargetId="figure-10@25.[324,1263,412,1649]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="Figs 58–63. Poecilosomella setimanus sp. n., male postabdomen and genitalia. 58 = sternite 5 of a paratype, ventral view, 59 = ventral part of epandrium with cerci and subepandrial sclerite (holotype, most of the epandrial setae omitted), 60 = surstylus of the holotype in broadest extension (a sublateral view), 61 = postgonite of the holotype, broadest extension, in a ± lateral view, 62 = same, of a paratype, 63 = basiphallus with postgonite of a paratype, lateral view. Scales: 0.2 mm for Fig. 58, 0.1" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5731972" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5731972/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">59–60</figureCitation>
). Mid basitarsus (usually longer) with rows of at least 1 anteroventral and 1 posteroventral rows of small flexible, mostly not black setae. 4
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="30" pageNumber="39">
<paragraph blockId="30.[317,1270,879,1293]" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">
<keyLead pageId="30" pageNumber="39">
4 Genal seta always present, moderate or strong. Wings not intensively patterned, costa overruns apex of 
<collectionCode box="[768,788,915,941]" country="Chile" name="Departamento de Geologia, Universidad de Chile" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">R</collectionCode>
<subScript attach="left" box="[788,817,929,945]" fontSize="7" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">4+5</subScript>
considerably, a vein appendage at terminal curvature of vein 
<collectionCode box="[711,731,950,976]" country="Chile" name="Departamento de Geologia, Universidad de Chile" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">R</collectionCode>
<subScript attach="left" box="[730,760,964,980]" fontSize="7" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">2+3</subScript>
present or absent. Male sternite 6 and 7 complex with large medial parts, forming a second vault below epandrium. Cerci (pseudocerci) without large lobes, caudally with or without 2 ridges. Subepandrial sclerites broader than high. Surstylus consist largely of 3 parts: caudal process with large black thick thorn, cranial lobe with more or less long setae and a “membranous” smaller lobe between them, which bears shorter thin setae. Postgonite with thin basal half and broad apical half, latter covered by thin hairs (at least partly). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Duda" baseAuthorityName="DUDA" baseAuthorityYear="1925" box="[587,769,1232,1258]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Poecilosomella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longecostata">
<emphasis box="[587,769,1232,1258]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">P. longecostata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group (
<taxonomicName authority="L. PAPP, 1990" authorityName="L. PAPP" authorityYear="1990" box="[954,1264,1231,1258]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Poecilosomella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capensis">
<emphasis box="[954,1088,1232,1258]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">P. capensis</emphasis>
L. 
<bibRefCitation author="PAPP, L." box="[1128,1264,1231,1257]" pageId="30" pageNumber="39" pagination="133 - 151" refId="ref16720" refString="PAPP, L. (1990) A review of the Afrotropical species of Poecilosomella Duda (Diptera, Sphaeroceridae). Annales historico-naturales Musei nationalis hungarici 81 (1989): 133 - 151." type="journal article" year="1990">PAPP, 1990</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Papp, 2010" authorityName="Papp" authorityYear="2010" box="[430,615,1267,1293]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Poecilosomella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kittenbergeri" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[430,615,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">P. kittenbergeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[622,687,1267,1293]" pageId="30" pageNumber="39" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(DUDA, 1925)" authorityName="Duda" baseAuthorityName="DUDA" baseAuthorityYear="1925" box="[699,1059,1267,1293]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Poecilosomella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longecostata">
<emphasis box="[699,882,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">P. longecostata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="DUDA, O." box="[898,1050,1267,1293]" pageId="30" pageNumber="39" pagination="5 - 215" refId="ref16563" refString="DUDA, O. (1925) Die aussereuropaischen Arten der Gattung Leptocera Olivier - Limosina Macquart (Dipteren) mit Berucksichtigung der europaischen Arten. Archiv fur Naturgeschichte 90 A (1924): 5 - 215." type="journal article" year="1925">DUDA, 1925</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Papp, 2010" authorityName="Papp" authorityYear="2010" box="[1071,1189,1267,1293]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Poecilosomella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="occulta" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[1071,1189,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">P. occulta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1197,1260,1267,1293]" pageId="30" pageNumber="39" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
)
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[317,1270,1319,1416]" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">
<keyLead pageId="30" pageNumber="39">
– Other set of characters. Other 
<taxonomicName box="[716,953,1355,1381]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Poecilosomella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[716,897,1355,1381]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">Poecilosomella</emphasis>
spp.
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName authority="L. PAPP, 1990" authorityName="L. PAPP" authorityYear="1990" box="[970,1264,1355,1381]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Poecilosomella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arnaudi">
<emphasis box="[970,1095,1355,1381]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">P. arnaudi</emphasis>
L. 
<bibRefCitation author="PAPP, L." box="[1126,1264,1355,1381]" pageId="30" pageNumber="39" pagination="133 - 151" refId="ref16720" refString="PAPP, L. (1990) A review of the Afrotropical species of Poecilosomella Duda (Diptera, Sphaeroceridae). Annales historico-naturales Musei nationalis hungarici 81 (1989): 133 - 151." type="journal article" year="1990">PAPP, 1990</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Papp, 2010" authorityName="Papp" authorityYear="2010" box="[481,661,1390,1416]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Poecilosomella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="duploseriata" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[481,661,1390,1416]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">P. duploseriata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[669,734,1390,1416]" pageId="30" pageNumber="39" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Papp, 2010" authorityName="Papp" authorityYear="2010" box="[746,896,1390,1416]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Poecilosomella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="setimanus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[746,896,1390,1416]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">P. setimanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[904,966,1390,1416]" pageId="30" pageNumber="39" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Papp, 2010" authorityName="Papp" authorityYear="2010" box="[1023,1190,1390,1416]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Poecilosomella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="setosissima" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[1023,1190,1390,1416]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">P. setosissima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1197,1260,1390,1416]" pageId="30" pageNumber="39" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
)
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="30" pageNumber="39">
<paragraph blockId="30.[317,1270,1443,1539]" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">
<keyLead pageId="30" pageNumber="39">
5 First radial cell with an additional crossvein, halving cell into two. A single long fronto-orbital seta present. 
<collectingCountry box="[785,850,1478,1504]" name="Togo" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">Togo</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[862,927,1478,1504]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">Zaire</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[938,1032,1478,1504]" name="Uganda" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">Uganda</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1044,1117,1478,1504]" name="Sudan" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">Sudan</collectingCountry>
<taxonomicName authority="VANSCHUYTBROECK, 1951" authorityName="VANSCHUYTBROECK" authorityYear="1951" box="[797,1270,1513,1539]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Poecilosomella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mirabilis">
<emphasis box="[797,935,1513,1539]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">P. mirabilis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="VANSCHUYTBROECK, P." box="[943,1270,1513,1539]" pageId="30" pageNumber="39" pagination="1 - 20" refId="ref16957" refString="VANSCHUYTBROECK, P. (1951) Contribution a l'etude des Sphaeroceridae africains (Diptera Acalyptratae) (3 me note). Bulletin Institut royal des Sciences naturelles de Belgique, Bruxelles 27 (41): 1 - 20." type="journal article" year="1951">VANSCHUYTBROECK, 1951</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[317,1270,1566,1592]" box="[317,1270,1566,1592]" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">
<keyLead box="[317,1270,1566,1592]" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">– First radial cell normal. Two pairs of fronto-orbital setae 6</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep lastPageId="31" lastPageNumber="40" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">
<paragraph blockId="30.[317,1270,1619,1750]" lastBlockId="31.[408,1270,439,536]" lastPageId="31" lastPageNumber="40" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">
<keyLead lastPageId="31" lastPageNumber="40" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">
6 All fore basitarsus light. Costal vein continued distinctly beyond apex of 
<collectionCode box="[408,428,1654,1680]" country="Chile" name="Departamento de Geologia, Universidad de Chile" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">R</collectionCode>
<subScript attach="left" box="[427,457,1668,1684]" fontSize="7" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">4+5</subScript>
. Vein 
<collectionCode box="[532,552,1654,1680]" country="Chile" name="Departamento de Geologia, Universidad de Chile" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">R</collectionCode>
<subScript attach="left" box="[552,581,1668,1684]" fontSize="7" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">4+5</subScript>
strongly, S-shaped sinuate. Vein 
<collectionCode box="[968,988,1654,1680]" country="Chile" name="Departamento de Geologia, Universidad de Chile" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">R</collectionCode>
<subScript attach="left" box="[988,1017,1668,1684]" fontSize="7" pageId="30" pageNumber="39">2+3</subScript>
with vein appendage. Genal seta rather weak. Also anterior katepisternal seta distinct. Abdominal tergites 1 and 2 conspicuously desclerotised medially. Male surstylus very large, with extremely large cranially curved process and very thick strong apical thorn. Widespread in Africa 
<taxonomicName authority="(VANSCHUYTBROECK, 1950)" baseAuthorityName="VANSCHUYTBROECK" baseAuthorityYear="1950" box="[790,1269,510,536]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Poecilosomella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maxima">
<emphasis box="[790,916,510,536]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="40">P. maxima</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="VANSCHUYTBROECK, P." box="[932,1261,510,536]" pageId="31" pageNumber="40" pagination="5 - 46" refId="ref16919" refString="VANSCHUYTBROECK, P. (1950) Dipteres Sphaeroceridae du Musee du Congo belge. Annales du Musee du Congo Belge, Tervuren, Serie in 8 o (Sciences Zoologiques) 5: 5 - 46." type="journal article" year="1950">VANSCHUYTBROECK, 1950</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[317,1270,563,729]" pageId="31" pageNumber="40">
<keyLead pageId="31" pageNumber="40">
– At least base of fore basitarsus dark. Costal vein terminates at apex of 
<collectionCode box="[1213,1233,563,589]" country="Chile" name="Departamento de Geologia, Universidad de Chile" pageId="31" pageNumber="40">R</collectionCode>
<subScript attach="left" box="[1233,1263,577,593]" fontSize="7" pageId="31" pageNumber="40">4+5</subScript>
. Vein 
<collectionCode box="[473,493,598,624]" country="Chile" name="Departamento de Geologia, Universidad de Chile" pageId="31" pageNumber="40">R</collectionCode>
<subScript attach="left" box="[492,522,612,628]" fontSize="7" pageId="31" pageNumber="40">4+5</subScript>
less strongly, not S-shaped curved. Vein 
<collectionCode box="[1014,1034,598,624]" country="Chile" name="Departamento de Geologia, Universidad de Chile" pageId="31" pageNumber="40">R</collectionCode>
<subScript attach="left" box="[1034,1063,612,628]" fontSize="7" pageId="31" pageNumber="40">2+3</subScript>
mostly without a vein appendage. Desclerotisation of abdominal tergites 1 and 2 indistinct. Male surstylus smaller, compact, without a cranially curved process and only with a small apical thorn. 7
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="31" pageNumber="40">
<paragraph blockId="31.[317,1270,756,1170]" pageId="31" pageNumber="40">
<keyLead pageId="31" pageNumber="40">
7 Mid basitarsus with 3 rows of stronger setae: an anterior row, a strong anteroventral row and a complete row of posteroventral setae. Dorsal half of male hind tibia with normal setae. Male genitalia (
<bibRefCitation author="PAPP, L." box="[1072,1210,827,853]" pageId="31" pageNumber="40" pagination="101 - 122" refId="ref16756" refString="PAPP, L. (1991) A review of the Oriental species of Poecilosomella Duda (Diptera, Sphaeroceridae). Acta Zoologica Academiae Scientiarum Hungaricae 37 (1 - 2): 101 - 122." type="journal article" year="1991">PAPP 1991</bibRefCitation>
: figs 6–10): cerci less separated from epandrium (fig. 6), apical thorn of surstylus longer and more caudally positioned (figs 7–8), than in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Papp" authorityYear="2010" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Poecilosomella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parangulata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="40">P. parangulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; postgonite (fig. 10) curved, angular in lateral view, apical part narrower and its setulae longer. Female spermathecae (
<bibRefCitation author="PAPP, L." box="[1054,1187,967,993]" pageId="31" pageNumber="40" pagination="133 - 151" refId="ref16720" refString="PAPP, L. (1990) A review of the Afrotropical species of Poecilosomella Duda (Diptera, Sphaeroceridae). Annales historico-naturales Musei nationalis hungarici 81 (1989): 133 - 151." type="journal article" year="1990">PAPP 1990</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 1) slightly ovoid, sclerotised ducts somewhat shorter than in 
<emphasis box="[1072,1255,1003,1029]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="40">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Papp" authorityYear="2010" box="[1072,1252,1003,1029]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Poecilosomella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parangulata">P. parangulata</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Originally Afrotropical, but human activity has made it widespread in South and Central America (incl. the Caribbean’s) and also in North America up to Florida and Texas; in the Palaearctic found on the Canary Is. 
<taxonomicName authority="(THOMSON, 1869)" baseAuthorityName="THOMSON" baseAuthorityYear="1869" box="[909,1269,1143,1170]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Poecilosomella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angulata">
<emphasis box="[909,1045,1144,1170]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="40">P. angulata</emphasis>
(THOMSON, 1869)
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[317,1270,1196,1540]" pageId="31" pageNumber="40">
<keyLead pageId="31" pageNumber="40">
– Only the anteroventral row of setae is strong on mid basitarsus; only 2 or 3 posteroventral setae present and only thin normal setae are in the anterior row. Dorsal half of male hind tibia with short thick sharp spiniform setae (
<figureCitation box="[416,500,1302,1328]" captionStart="Figs 33–35" captionStartId="16.[317,360,1757,1778]" captionTargetBox="[322,1265,735,1722]" captionTargetId="figure-156@16.[317,1269,729,1725]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Figs 33–35. Poecilosomella parangulata sp. n., paratype male. 33 = hind tibia, dorsal view, 34 = sternite 5, ventral view, 35 = epandrium with modified cerci and subepandrial sclerite, caudal view. Scales: 0.2 mm for Figs 34–35, 0.4 mm for Fig. 33" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5731960" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5731960/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="40">Fig. 33</figureCitation>
). Male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[695,828,1302,1328]" captionStart-0="Figs 33–35" captionStart-1="Figs 36–41" captionStartId-0="16.[317,360,1757,1778]" captionStartId-1="18.[317,360,1694,1715]" captionTargetBox-0="[322,1265,735,1722]" captionTargetBox-1="[348,1241,433,1666]" captionTargetId-0="figure-156@16.[317,1269,729,1725]" captionTargetId-1="figure-16@18.[343,1244,424,1666]" captionTargetPageId-0="16" captionTargetPageId-1="18" captionText-0="Figs 33–35. Poecilosomella parangulata sp. n., paratype male. 33 = hind tibia, dorsal view, 34 = sternite 5, ventral view, 35 = epandrium with modified cerci and subepandrial sclerite, caudal view. Scales: 0.2 mm for Figs 34–35, 0.4 mm for Fig. 33" captionText-1="Figs 36–41. Poecilosomella parangulata sp. n., paratype male, postabdomen and genitalia. 36–37 = surstylus in broadest (sublateral) view: 36 = outer view, 37 = inner (medial) view, 38 = hypandrium, dorsal view, 39 = postgonite in widest extension, i.e. sublateral view, 40 = basiphallus and phallapodeme, lateral view (outset: caudal part in higher magnification), 41 = distiphallus, dorsal view. Scales: 0.2 mm for Figs 36–38, 40, 0.1 mm for Figs 39, 41" figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5731960" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5731962" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/5731960/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/5731962/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="40">Figs 34–41</figureCitation>
): cerci more separated from epandrium (
<figureCitation box="[416,505,1337,1363]" captionStart="Figs 33–35" captionStartId="16.[317,360,1757,1778]" captionTargetBox="[322,1265,735,1722]" captionTargetId="figure-156@16.[317,1269,729,1725]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Figs 33–35. Poecilosomella parangulata sp. n., paratype male. 33 = hind tibia, dorsal view, 34 = sternite 5, ventral view, 35 = epandrium with modified cerci and subepandrial sclerite, caudal view. Scales: 0.2 mm for Figs 34–35, 0.4 mm for Fig. 33" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5731960" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5731960/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="40">Fig. 35</figureCitation>
), apical thorn of surstylus shorter and more centrally positioned (
<figureCitation box="[416,552,1372,1398]" captionStart="Figs 36–41" captionStartId="18.[317,360,1694,1715]" captionTargetBox="[348,1241,433,1666]" captionTargetId="figure-16@18.[343,1244,424,1666]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Figs 36–41. Poecilosomella parangulata sp. n., paratype male, postabdomen and genitalia. 36–37 = surstylus in broadest (sublateral) view: 36 = outer view, 37 = inner (medial) view, 38 = hypandrium, dorsal view, 39 = postgonite in widest extension, i.e. sublateral view, 40 = basiphallus and phallapodeme, lateral view (outset: caudal part in higher magnification), 41 = distiphallus, dorsal view. Scales: 0.2 mm for Figs 36–38, 40, 0.1 mm for Figs 39, 41" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5731962" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5731962/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="40">Figs 36–37</figureCitation>
), than in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="THOMSON" baseAuthorityYear="1869" box="[657,793,1372,1398]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Poecilosomella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angulata">
<emphasis box="[657,793,1372,1398]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="40">P. angulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; postgonite (
<figureCitation box="[945,1030,1372,1398]" captionStart="Figs 36–41" captionStartId="18.[317,360,1694,1715]" captionTargetBox="[348,1241,433,1666]" captionTargetId="figure-16@18.[343,1244,424,1666]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Figs 36–41. Poecilosomella parangulata sp. n., paratype male, postabdomen and genitalia. 36–37 = surstylus in broadest (sublateral) view: 36 = outer view, 37 = inner (medial) view, 38 = hypandrium, dorsal view, 39 = postgonite in widest extension, i.e. sublateral view, 40 = basiphallus and phallapodeme, lateral view (outset: caudal part in higher magnification), 41 = distiphallus, dorsal view. Scales: 0.2 mm for Figs 36–38, 40, 0.1 mm for Figs 39, 41" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5731962" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5731962/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="40">Fig. 39</figureCitation>
) not angular curved, apical part thicker and its setulae shorter. Some of the female genital parts (
<figureCitation box="[416,556,1443,1469]" captionStart="Figs 42–45" captionStartId="19.[317,360,1724,1745]" captionTargetBox="[322,1264,960,1696]" captionTargetId="figure-185@19.[320,1266,955,1696]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Figs 42–45. Poecilosomella parangulata sp. n., paratype female, postabdomen and genitalia. 42 = outlines of the female postabdomen, caudal view, 43 = epiproct, dorsal view; 44 = sternite 8, ventral view, 45 = spermathecae (one of the paired ones reduced), lateral view. Scales: 0.2 mm for Figs 42–44, 0.1 mm for Fig. 45" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5731964" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5731964/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="40">Figs 42–45</figureCitation>
) also characteristic, spermathecae (
<figureCitation box="[995,1086,1443,1469]" captionStart="Figs 42–45" captionStartId="19.[317,360,1724,1745]" captionTargetBox="[322,1264,960,1696]" captionTargetId="figure-185@19.[320,1266,955,1696]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Figs 42–45. Poecilosomella parangulata sp. n., paratype female, postabdomen and genitalia. 42 = outlines of the female postabdomen, caudal view, 43 = epiproct, dorsal view; 44 = sternite 8, ventral view, 45 = spermathecae (one of the paired ones reduced), lateral view. Scales: 0.2 mm for Figs 42–44, 0.1 mm for Fig. 45" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5731964" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5731964/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="40">Fig. 45</figureCitation>
) globular with slightly longer sclerotised ducts than 
<emphasis box="[845,1012,1478,1504]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="40">
in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="THOMSON" baseAuthorityYear="1869" box="[875,1012,1478,1504]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Poecilosomella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angulata">P. angulata</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
. Southern Africa 
<taxonomicName authority="Papp, 2010" authorityName="Papp" authorityYear="2010" box="[1014,1199,1514,1540]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Poecilosomella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parangulata" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1014,1199,1514,1540]" pageId="31" pageNumber="40">P. parangulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1207,1269,1514,1540]" pageId="31" pageNumber="40" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
</key>
